Last Blood Duel: MP3 Players vs Cell Phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
This makes it clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why you should find a self-employed reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to our latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LPs and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls are crowded on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
There are also price and quality categories here.
For some it can be unacceptable to spend for a reader 8 thousand crowns, as well as a fan of Pink Floyd perhaps hardly digests the headphones from twenty crowns of the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is the life of the batteries that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, which is something that mobile phones don’t even do by mistake.
There is no other device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, calling and texting, it can read music and video, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even can navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle that no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the screen will require a charger.
Reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few mobile phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, the music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
When it comes to cheap mobile phones, don’t count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add us, from time to time, some calls, get to work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst last at least 9 hours with continuous functionality with a charge.
An additional problem arises when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do without an adapter for the minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, with some exceptions (iPod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create their own media library, sorted by the name of the performers, album name, genre or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the folder tree structure, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, focus on battery strength, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs, and clearly ease of use.
If you need music above all as a background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This is possible now, clearly on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about which formats your phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular, the vast majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited only to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something frowns in their pocket while the MP3 player remains forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always wear the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for common headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
The advantage of readers is, among others, easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our selection) and anyone who handles them can do it.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling at one time with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally hitting the start-up of the mobile internet network and consequently a giant bill for the transmission of data.
What device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, they fall within the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive can do it even with the 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you must not spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, preferably take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of service thus approaches the same MP3 player.
In this regard, Sony Ericsson has made more progress, which walkman line phones have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands ensure the same service and the same price category up to 4,000 kronor, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, in general up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Possibly.
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
