Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in terms of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent Authorities -with Complicit Operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the creation of U:fon testify that when operators hold onto one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure against <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
