In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the extensive theme park on the suburbs of Orlando, a few miles from the splendour, noise, huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated into the country and the home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, the most famous writer of Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city that he described – and that makes tourists stop by understanding it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a separate place.
It is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little about us, doesn't know what he's missing."
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on race, many here remain distrustful of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of rural Southern Black culture—sometimes despised, sometimes rewarded—born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida into a scenario of black history and human drama.
Low as a big box in both life and literature, Hurston brought readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Outside the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always cared about, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned the widow's new husband Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the passage rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly, this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora used to say it like it was," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls whom Hurston immortalizes by quoting men who sing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moving to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston plunged into the city, he usually arrived without notice in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts of decent clothing today.
Many residents were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others were whispering.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on his chair in the backyard above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plaqueless tomb in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big commemorative ceremonies, and no big conferences.
"I don't think they understand her contribution to the world or her legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a 2003 Hurston biography.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officers wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane highway.
Orlando’s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city’s western boundary.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended its idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's home door.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and stuff to the people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a crocodile out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, defining his decision in Brown against the school office as "an insult rather than an honor to my race".
Residents now say that the segregation of schools, despite being positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of his youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember this - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't embrace your white teacher because your white teacher...- I mean, there's a cultural divide there," said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons – black writer, actress and artist who surpassed prejudices, as she did, with joyful self-confidence and lines like: “How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I can't really understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long walk through Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway hit the bookshelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The design of the highway came just as his most famous daughter had turned the lights on again.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its road project.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway have brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city," Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project has helped to change the image the city has of itself.
Those from outside the city like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the public historical register in 1998.
A new one-story bookstore (named Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a refurbished and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: only six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road under the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for the story of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permit requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, to some things—such as the murals on Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man, that make black men appear in the fields—do not have permission to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weak for bright red, still fear their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of civic pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, neither better, nor worse and proud, creative, great worker, silly and confused as other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection what can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s grandson, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said may need help.
And even those younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"A lot of people, if they just got in here, will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Kenon said after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
