Speaking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but it really doesn’t matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called sleepiness.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, nighttime enuresis (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stressful situations or over-excitation.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or that the opposite happens (screaming, screaming, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a result of the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, however, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcit the baby before going to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiresome to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleepers appear they try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him for information.
You will not get anything, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not to see what he is dreaming to say, so you need to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it might lead.
Never tell your child that you might ask him/her questions at night to learn his/her secrets.
Not even for a joke.
Such a thing causes a great anguish.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing serious, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
