The meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the infected blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such drama and popular protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, directed by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at shedding light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminating recommendations to prevent the resurgence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was delayed in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever relationship, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and the Société canadienne du sang (Société canadienne du sang) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was deadly.
Thanks to ongoing efforts to improve the safety of blood tests and field research over the next few years, we have regained public confidence," she said, proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec already had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says she who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It is therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for some years, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us so much that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to that in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them has thus significantly decreased.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by a transfusion is detected.
I believe that today we can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
“The needs are increasing as the population ages.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who make up on average only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory that can meet the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But the members of this group of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it is hard to find an hour to donate blood," says depressed Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec which manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth cord blood sample and we expect to take more than a thousand of them each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection practice as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed to not be able to access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
