Free Opinion - The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and CEO of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small squatted publishing house with the intention of launching a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, writers and the publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend a considerable amount of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers funded by the nearly bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Incidentally, in these odd-armed struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that would overwhelm the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to speak again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that it should have presented its own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates usually take place with an exchange of views and not at a whim.
It would therefore have been sufficient for the society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is well evident?
In the world of the vice president, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the perfumed lawyers and not to the whole of the Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even defamers have a right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports Black Canada’s authors and publishers does so primarily because they reject the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to the Barrick and to judge, but based on civilian exchanges of opinion, and not in the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of ambush (searching for the "public debate", the Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Black an ultimatum urging them to suspend the parutil...
Beyond Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrack Gold lawsuit constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies in blocks the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are uncomfortable to the richest companies in the world, punishing multiple lawsuits, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific norms as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are part, has been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it is not seeking a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the university world, just as it is affected by the same public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit abusive lawsuits.
