The Psychology of Excess Bidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neuroscientists and economists at the University of New York have managed to discover the neuro-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in Science magazine, men don’t want to stay behind in a competition like eBay’s auction, so they’re available to pay even a higher price.
The research attempted to trace the nervous pattern of this “match” at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in a auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex enters intensively into operation when you lose to the game.
This area of the brain, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the stretched body.
To support their theory, the group’s economists conducted a financial follow-up survey.
In this investigation, three groups tendered against a partner under different conditions.
To the control group they reported how much the actual value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
In addition to this, they promised that in the event of a win, they will receive another prize of $15.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the group members would lose the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss was emphasized.
By checking the neuroscientists' hypothesis, the members of the team who played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winning".
"These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These, in fact, so far explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging helped solve the contradiction between the two theories, so we came to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
In Hungary the number of patients with hepatitis amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are cured: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and caused diseases differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leaks, saliva).
It is useful for travelers to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellow spots form on the skin and on the white of the eyes, stools become clear and dark urine, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens deceptively destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed people.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Because even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease is worth talking to your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 worldwide by disease associations.
The purpose is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out to 12 Catholic believers and to as many atheists, while everyone was observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of research in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also take part.
The test took place exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the seventeenth century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's handkerchief painted in the fifteenth century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious state among the believers, while the painting of Leonardo was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and was considered to have a tranquilizing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time zone received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "have calmed down and were permeated with peace".
Looking at the religious image they realized 12% less pain than when they had before them the work of Leonardo.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you need to find the right image.
“We have to look for an image that they feel very positive towards, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality,” Wright said.
After the excellent results remains only the question whether the painting of a Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of similar calibre is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
