Intelligent Machine Imitates Squirrel Flight
What could be the best method to develop collision protection technologies if they do not imitate the obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the slingshots gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic impetus on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-car with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development, explained at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300-degree view in each direction.
The engineers drew on the idea of telemetric laser to copy the function of the bee's sight.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the robot senses the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a way different from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If it weren’t for that, the robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the more harmful and innermost layer of the shield, within which the collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in a blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to the bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a high energy density, which means that their lifespan is longer than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few dozen Kb.
There is no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a collision avoidance technology that, according to Nissan, can be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Further application possibilities can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system, which by avoiding obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
