Mercandelli also denounced the "progressive deterioration of the levels of compensation protection envisaged for the victims of work" and the "assistanceal drift towards which the system has been pushing in recent years".
"The objective is therefore to return to the worker the insurance guarantee - he added - so that the fate of those who are injured does not have to depend on spontaneities or allowances from time to time ordered by the legislator".
MP3 players accused of putting their hearing at risk
Listening to loud music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission reports, citing the opinion of the EU's Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csserri), published today in a statement released in Brussels.
"From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the loud volume device risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high levels of audibility may unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
“From the scientific findings, a clear risk emerges and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable musical equipment and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise caused by it.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music equipment and related equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
You can greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment if they listen to loud music for only 5 hours per week (more than 89 decibels) exceed the currently in force limits for maximum permitted noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk permanent loss of hearing after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
