Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already emerged a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times confirms this by informing us that the current crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of the South, and strong in the Central and Central states.
The soul, by the way, which has become arrogantly alive with the vow of which I spoke at the beginning.
But this is only an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps foretells or already lets us see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of long-incubated phenomena that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, yes, close ties with abroad, but that first and foremost see the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and those families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or has little to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union, which, as usual, is divided between the different interests and between the different state strategies and cannot decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all disbursement of funds: since when it comes to the narrows it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in the sixth place.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization will ever have a similar amount.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, after all, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to take account of those things that are very little immaterial.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but are still absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So those who find themselves to be sovereign certainly possess several more cards than those who are not, to those who are unlucky to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, however, which foreshadows a fracture.
He who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need of authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation into their own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, especially economic ones, proved so inadequate and full of shadow areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and, in a certain sense, disturbing: a discredit, an insufficiency, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
In other words, it seems that the belief that before their actions are the same as the ideas of the social elites so far in existence, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the general sense of the term, to have made their time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority, is becoming more and more common.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly feeds a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and of the traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and most recent times.
It has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, someone would say, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what from today is not taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis may be regurgitated.
In the face of all this, to speak of a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
Keeping your eyes open is certainly not for nothing.
