Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities erase the historical halls
Historical cinemas close in favor of Multiplex.
“A city without cinema is a blind city, it is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multisale and the consequent death by consumption of the monosale in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that seem inevitable and incontrovertible to us but also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and loads of memory,"it is as if he was missing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the street and so many emotions", observes the director of New cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago was worth to Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and which tells the story of the no salava for the province
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed the 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay for the major scotto are mainly the rooms in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of ANEC, “it is useful that new structures are built, but we should ensure the survival of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its attendees are willing to move to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favour of the operators: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect the existing laws.
To support the sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between Comune and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote the monosaal cinemas both in the historic center and in the suburbs.
Among the rules envisaged are tax relief measures in favour of the operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for the stop and in some parking lots.
"It's an initiative that I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counteract the overpowering of multiplexes, traditional halls also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradise", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have lived so many shared emotions, to not see the signs blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
