When the energy is born from the waves now the big ones come into the field.
It is an endless deposit, which occupies over 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have set their eyes, and now they are trying to put their hands, giants like the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, at the same time as the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmental urges and the new rise in oil give momentum to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore wind farms.
This amount would be twice that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be the currents and tides.
I collided with the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy and among these companies have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a U.S. oil giant company told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a signal not least, especially considering that it is in Alaska that the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York's Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey's Ocean Power are on the road to energy coming from the sea, and the amounts invested so far, though not known in detail, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still at the dawn, also so that marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to cause major problems to the ecosystem.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boe connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the boe up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now, there are four plants of this type under construction, awaiting only federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of the water when there are tides turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permissions to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electricity, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coast, have already invested $7 million in 2008 and planned investments of up to $35 million for 2009.
